# Trust boundary handlers

## Objective

Boundaries between **untrusted input** (HTTP requests, forms, external schedulers, other accounts) and **internal systems** (Supabase `service_role`, user mailboxes, shared caches) silently break OWASP audits. This rule encodes **four non-negotiable patterns** from the **2026-04 security review** plus related `docs/adr/`. Agents must confirm compliance before closing work touching listed surfaces.

## When this rule applies

Trigger review whenever the change touches:

1. Anything under **`src/app/api/cron/**`**, Stripe/Resend/other webhooks, or routes secured by shared secrets.
2. **`src/app/api/**` route handlers** emitting **per-user personalized** bodies (calendar feeds, signed URLs, receipt downloads, admin dashboards, …).
3. **Server actions/route handlers** invoking **`createAdminClient`** to mutate **another user’s** protected data (parent→ward, admin→student, tutor→student).
4. Flows **persisting human-authored HTML** (email templates, portal messages, CMS copy) later rendered through `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` or emailed verbatim.

If none apply, skip this rule.

## Pattern 1 — Cron/webhook secrets **must come from headers**

Secrets in query strings leak via **Referrer**, browser history, CDN/proxy logs, and accidental sharing. **Never** read cron/webhook secrets from `URL.searchParams` or unchecked public bodies.

- Acceptable: `Authorization: Bearer <SECRET>` (Vercel Cron) and `x-<provider>-secret`.
- **Mandatory:** reuse **`src/lib/auth/verifyCronRequest.ts`** (canonical helper) instead of per-route forks. New providers extend that helper or sibling modules under `src/lib/auth/`.

**Regression tests** must cover **401** when `?secret=…` sneaks through (see `src/__tests__/lib/auth/verifyCronRequest.test.ts`, `src/__tests__/api/recomputeMinorFlagsRoute.test.ts`).

> Real audit case (2026-04): every `/api/cron/*` route accepted `?secret=<CRON_SECRET>` leaking secrets whenever links were reused.

## Pattern 2 — `Cache-Control` for personalized payloads

Bodies depending on **user/session/private tokens** (ICS calendars, pupil exports, bespoke admin payloads) MUST send **`Cache-Control: private`** and, where applicable, **`no-store`/`no-cache`**.

- **Forbidden:** `Cache-Control: public` for personalized payloads—even opaque tokens can be mistakenly cached/shared by intermediaries.
- **Allowed:** `public, immutable` only for genuinely static assets served identically across users.

Regression tests verifying absence of sneaky **`public`** flags exist for ICS feeds (`src/__tests__/api/calendarFeedRoute.test.ts`).

> Audit case (2026-04): `/api/calendar/feed/[token]` returned `public, max-age=300`, letting caches serve one pupil’s ICS to unrelated clients.

## Pattern 3 — Cross-account mutations require **re-auth + audit + notifications**

Whenever `createAdminClient` mutates sensitive cross-account identifiers (credentials, MFA factors, guardianship links):

1. **Step-up verification** (`verifyUserPassword`/MFA) **before** `admin.auth.admin.updateUserById` or equivalent—not just session detection (stolen sessions fail password checks).
2. **Structured audit trails** persisted to **`system_config_audit`** (RLS-locked admin table) documenting `actor_id`, `action`, `resource_type`, `resource_id`, and scoped `payload` matching `recordSystemAudit` fidelity with real actor attribution.
3. **Notify impacted users** via **prior contact channels** whenever emails/phones/etc. mutate—mirror security alerts from hyperscalers.

New surfaces mandate ADR (**`10-engineering-governance.mdc`**). Canonical example: `docs/adr/2026-04-parent-ward-email-change-hardening.md` + `[locale]/dashboard/parent/children/[studentId]/actions.ts`.

> Prior bug: guardians could forcibly migrate ward login emails with confirmed flags without notifying previous addresses or auditors.

## Pattern 4 — Human-authored HTML must sanitize **at persistence**, not solely render-time

Stored HTML powering `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` or outbound rich mail MUST pass approved sanitizers during **mutation paths**:

- Messaging subset: `src/lib/messaging/sanitizeMessageHtml.ts`.
- Email template subset (`style`, anchors, mailto-safe): `src/lib/email/sanitizeEmailTemplateHtml.ts`.

Do **not** rely on attacker assumptions (“trusted admin/session”). Imports and compromised admins are realistic vectors.

Forbidden: sanitizing only in React previews while DB persists raw markup—multi-surfaces reuse that HTML (exports, SSR, transactional mail).

Blanking sanitizer outputs → **`invalid_input`** semantics (do not silently persist worthless markup).

Mandatory tests verifying persisted payloads strip `<script>`, dangerous `on*`, `javascript:`, risky `data:` URIs (`src/__tests__/app/emailTemplateActions.test.ts`, `src/__tests__/lib/email/sanitizeEmailTemplateHtml.test.ts`).

## Agent closing checklist

- [ ] Cron/webhook paths reject query/body-secret bypasses (+ tests asserting `401` paths).
- [ ] Personalized HTTP responses carry **private/no-store** caches (tests guarding `public`).
- [ ] Cross-account admin flows include **step-up auth**, **`system_config_audit` rows**, notifications/ADR linkage.
- [ ] Persisted editable HTML sanitized server-side everywhere + automated proof.

